A New Era of Reproductive Rights

With the historic step forward of legalizing the provision of abortion services in both Argentina and Uruguay in 2018 and the ongoing global push against restrictive reproductive health policies, history looks to be repeating itself with Suriname’s desire to join these Latin American visionaries.

ALSO READ: Argentina: The Birthplace of Legal Abortion Surpasses 50,000 Abortions Since Legalization

Narvila Sugrim, representative of Women and Home Health Foundation (WHH), the organization spearheading the country’s legalization efforts, believes that with “Rwanda and South Africa” already having passed abortion laws that include women’s bodily autonomy and reproductive rights, “it is time for Suriname” to do the same.

“I hope that when the parliament will discuss this bill, then they will take history into account,” she told VICE News.

The process says Sugrim, “will be painful, but will unnoticed lead to better outcomes in terms of women’s health.”
